The standard deviation is represented by the dotted lines in the data graphs. The curve showing the average over a 5-day period is based on real data, while the solid lines represent the raw data. The higher number of deaths predicted by the model may be due to underdetection (See Fig. 5). To analyze the impact of underdetection of COVID-19 in Argentina, we compared official death records from 2019 and 2020 for the same period (January 1 to April 30) [44]. Discrepancies between total deaths in comparison to COVID-19 records from WHO [42] and Argentinean government data [44] suggest significant underdetection of cases.

By modeling various scenarios, it was found that implementing a strict lockdown after 90 days led to a significant reduction in new cases and deaths compared to other approaches. Recovery time was also quicker, with new cases stopping earlier. The peak of new cases occurred on day 93 (June 1) and new deaths on day 106 (June 11). By day 300, there were 552,855 (± 195,802) diagnosed cases and 87,059 (± 30,871) deaths. Using hospitalization data from Fig. 3, estimates were made for occupied beds for regular and critical cases. Differences between diagnosed, undiagnosed, and recovered cases were also examined.
